\section{Introduction}
The Job Shop Scheduling Problem (JSSP) is a combinatorial optimization problem that involves scheduling a set of jobs on a set of machines where each job must be processed through a specific sequence of operations on different machines. Each operation requires a specific machine for a predetermined amount of time, and each machine can process only one operation at a time.

The JSSP is classified as an NP-hard problem, meaning that finding an optimal solution becomes computationally intractable as the problem size increases. This complexity arises from the factorial growth in the number of possible schedules as the number of jobs and machines increases. For example, a problem with $n$ jobs and $m$ machines can have up to $(n!)^m$ possible schedules.

JSSP has significant practical relevance in manufacturing systems, production planning, and resource allocation, where efficient scheduling directly impacts cost and throughput.

The primary objective in most JSSP variants is to minimize the makespan, which is the total time required to complete all jobs. Reducing the makespan leads to increased productivity, better resource utilization, reduced operational costs, and improved customer satisfaction through faster delivery times. Given its practical importance and computational complexity, the JSSP continues to be an active area of research in both academia and industry.

\section{Formal Problem Definition}

The Job Shop Scheduling Problem can be formally defined using the following parameters and components:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $n$ = number of jobs to be scheduled
    \item $m$ = number of machines available
    \item $J = \{J_1, J_2, \ldots, J_n\}$ = set of jobs
    \item $M = \{M_1, M_2, \ldots, M_m\}$ = set of machines
    \item $O_{ij}$ = operation $i$ of job $j$
    \item $p_{ij}$ = processing time of operation $O_{ij}$
    \item $m_{ij}$ = machine required to process operation $O_{ij}$
    \item $s_{ij}$ = starting time of operation $O_{ij}$
    \item $C_{ij}$ = completion time of operation $O_{ij}$
    \item $C_{\max}$ = makespan (maximum completion time among all jobs)
\end{itemize}

