\subsection{Decision Variables}

The decision variables are the starting times $s_{ij}$ for each operation $O_{ij}$. These determine when each operation begins on its assigned machine and, together with the precedence and machine capacity constraints, fully define the schedule. In the operation-based permutation encoding used by our metaheuristic, the decision is equivalently represented as the ordering of operations within the permutation vector.

\subsection{Objective Function}

The primary objective is to minimize the makespan $C_{\max}$:

\[
\text{Minimize } C_{\max}
\]

where $C_{\max}$ represents the maximum completion time among all jobs:

\[
C_{\max} = \max_{j=1,\ldots,n} \{C_j\}
\]

Here, $C_j$ denotes the completion time of the last operation of job $j$.


\subsection{Constraints}

The problem must satisfy the following constraints:

\textbf{1. Precedence Constraints:} Operations within the same job must be processed in their predetermined order. For each job $j$ and consecutive operations $i$ and $i+1$:
\[
s_{i+1,j} \geq s_{ij} + p_{ij}
\]
This ensures that operation $(i+1)$ of job $j$ can only start after operation $i$ of job $j$ is completed.

\textbf{2. Machine Capacity Constraints:} Each machine can process at most one operation at a time. For any two operations $O_{ij}$ and $O_{k\ell}$ that require the same machine:
\[
s_{k\ell} \geq s_{ij} + p_{ij} \quad \text{or} \quad s_{ij} \geq s_{k\ell} + p_{k\ell}
\]
This ensures operations on the same machine do not overlap in time.

\textbf{3. Makespan Definition:} The makespan equals the maximum completion time among all jobs:
\[
C_{\max} \geq C_j \quad \forall j \in \{1, \ldots, n\}
\]
where $C_j$ is the completion time of job $j$ (i.e., the completion time of its last operation).



\textbf{4. Non-negativity:} All starting times must be non-negative:
\[
s_{ij} \geq 0 \quad \forall i,j
\]

\section{Dataset or Benchmark Instances}

For this project, we will use Demirkol's benchmark instances, which are well-established in the job shop scheduling research community. These instances were introduced by \cite{DEMIRKOL1998137} and have been widely used to evaluate the performance of scheduling algorithms.

\subsection{Benchmark Description}

This benchmark set consists of 80 problem instances with varying characteristics:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Problem Sizes:} The instances range from small to large scale problems
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Small: 20 jobs $\times$ 15 machines, 20 jobs $\times$ 20 machines
        \item Medium: 30 jobs $\times$ 15 machines, 30 jobs $\times$ 20 machines
        \item Large: 40 jobs $\times$ 15 machines, 40 jobs $\times$ 20 machines
        \item Extra-large: 50 jobs $\times$ 15 machines, 50 jobs $\times$ 20 machines
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Instance Types:} Two main categories based on objective function
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \texttt{rcmax}: Regular completion time maximization problems (instances 1--40)
        \item \texttt{cscmax}: Customer service completion maximization problems (instances 41--80)
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Instance File Format}

Each benchmark instance file contains the problem data in the following format:

\begin{itemize}
\item First line: number of jobs ($n$) and number of machines ($m$)
\item Following lines: For each job, the sequence of operations with their machine assignments and processing times
\item Format per operation: (machine\_id, processing\_time) pairs
\end{itemize}

