\subsection{Selection Strategy}
We selected a diverse set of problems to test how our algorithm handles different scales and structures. Our selection includes 10 instances with 20 jobs and 20 instances with 30 jobs. The 20-job instances act as a starting point to measure basic performance on medium-sized problems, which involve about 300 to 400 total operations. The 30-job instances are the main focus, designed to challenge the algorithm with much larger search spaces. We divided these 30-job problems into two types, \textit{cscmax} and \textit{rcmax}, to see how the algorithm performs when the data is distributed differently.

\subsection{Justification of Diversity and Complexity}
Using both \textit{cscmax} and \textit{rcmax} types for the 30-job problems is important for testing the robustness of our approach. Even when the number of jobs and machines is the same, the processing times and sequences in these two sets follow different patterns. By testing both, we can prove whether our proposed algorithm can find high-quality solutions regardless of whether the data is purely random or contains specific bottlenecks. This variety ensures our results are reliable across different types of scheduling scenarios.

The difficulty of these problems grows exponentially as we add more jobs. In our mathematical model, a 30-job problem requires the algorithm to decide the order of jobs using $n(n-1)/2 = 435$ binary variables for every machine. This creates a significantly more complex search space than the 20-job version, which only requires 190 variables per machine. By choosing 30-job problems for the majority of our tests, we are putting our algorithm through a careful evaluation to see if it can effectively navigate very large and difficult optimization environments.

