\section{Proposed Approach}

\subsection{Overview Design and General Algorithm}
Simulated Annealing (SA) is a stochastic metaheuristic optimization algorithm inspired by the annealing process in metallurgy \citep{kirkpatrick1983}, where a material is heated and then slowly cooled to alter its physical properties and minimize its internal energy. In the context of combinatorial optimization, the energy state corresponds to the fitness value of a solution, and the temperature acts as a control parameter that dictates the probability of accepting worse solutions to escape local optima.

Unlike standard local search algorithms that only accept strictly improving moves, SA allows the exploration of suboptimal regions of the search space. Early in the search process, when the temperature is high, the algorithm possesses a higher probability of accepting worse solutions, promoting exploration. As the temperature systematically decreases according to a cooling schedule, the algorithm transitions into an exploitation phase, focusing on refining solutions in promising regions.

Algorithm 1 outlines the comprehensive structure of the proposed Simulated Annealing algorithm applied to the JSSP with the primary goal of minimizing the makespan $C_{max}$.

% ============================================================
% FIX: Pseudocode — line 10 corrected (s ← s')
% ============================================================
\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{Simulated Annealing for JSSP}
\label{alg:simulated_annealing}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\renewcommand{\algorithmicrequire}{\textbf{Input:}}
\renewcommand{\algorithmicensure}{\textbf{Output:}}
\REQUIRE $n$ jobs, $m$ machines, processing times $p_{ij}$, initial temperature $T_0$, cooling rate $\alpha$, termination temperature $T_{min}$, Markov chain length ($L$)
\ENSURE Best permutation $s^*$ and its makespan $C_{max}$

\STATE Generate a random initial solution $s$;
\STATE Evaluate its makespan $f(s)$ and set it as the current and best: $s^* \leftarrow s$;
\STATE Initialize temperature $T \leftarrow T_0$;

\WHILE{$T > T_{min}$}
    \FOR{iteration = 1 to $L$}
        \STATE Generate a random swap neighbor $s'$ of $s$;
        \STATE Evaluate its makespan $f(s')$;
        \STATE $\Delta E \leftarrow f(s') - f(s)$;
        
        \IF{$\Delta E \le 0$}
            \STATE $s \leftarrow s'$; \COMMENT{Accept better solution}
            \IF{$f(s') < f(s^*)$}
                \STATE $s^* \leftarrow s'$; \COMMENT{Update global best}
            \ENDIF
        \ELSE
            \STATE Generate a random number $r$ in range $[0, 1)$;
            \IF{$r < e^{-\frac{\Delta E}{T}}$}
                \STATE $s \leftarrow s'$; \COMMENT{Accept worse solution based on Metropolis criterion}
            \ENDIF
        \ENDIF
    \ENDFOR
    \STATE $T \leftarrow T \times \alpha$; \COMMENT{Cool down the system}
\ENDWHILE

\RETURN $s^*, f(s^*)$;
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\subsection{Solution Representation}
To maintain structural compatibility and ensure valid scheduling configurations, each solution is encoded using an \textit{operation-based permutation} string. In this vector representation, each job ID appears exactly $m$ times, where $m$ is the total number of available machines. The chronological appearance of a job ID from left to right directly maps to the progressive sequence of its operations. For instance, the first time a job index appears, it denotes its first operation; the second appearance represents its subsequent operation, and so forth.

For a representative $20 \times 15$ problem instance, the solution is represented as an array of length $300$:
\begin{equation}
s = [7, 15, 2, 5, 2, 16, 12, 8, 1, \dots]
\end{equation}

This representation is inherently feasible and structurally robust. Because operations for any given job are inherently evaluated in their correct operational sequence, precedence constraints are automatically satisfied without requiring specialized repair mechanisms or penalty functions.

\subsection{Fitness Function}
The fitness function measures the structural quality of a candidate sequence by computing its total makespan ($C_{max}$), representing the absolute completion time of all jobs. The calculation processes the operation-based permutation from left to right, scheduling each encountered operation dynamically. The earliest feasible start time ($s_{ij}$) for operation $i$ of job $j$ is strictly governed by the completion of its immediate predecessor operation and the availability of its designated machine:
\begin{equation}
s_{ij} = \max(\text{job\_ready\_time}_j, \text{machine\_ready\_time}_{m_{ij}})
\end{equation}

where $\text{job\_ready\_time}_j$ is the timestamp when job $j$ finishes its prior operation, and $\text{machine\_ready\_time}_{m_{ij}}$ is the moment the required machine becomes idle. The operation completion time is subsequently calculated as:
\begin{equation}
C_{ij} = s_{ij} + p_{ij}
\end{equation}

where $p_{ij}$ is the predetermined processing duration. Once all operations are placed within the timeline, the comprehensive makespan is extracted as:
\begin{equation}
C_{max} = \max_{j=1,\dots,n} C_j
\end{equation}

where $C_j$ represents the final completion timestamp of the last operation belonging to job $j$.

\subsection{Neighborhood Structure}
The neighborhood of an active schedule is explored by applying stochastic swap moves. A neighbor solution ($s'$) is generated by selecting two distinct indices at random within the 300-length permutation vector and interchanging their job values. To prevent redundant computational overhead, the algorithm explicitly ensures that the two selected positions contain different job IDs, as swapping identical values leaves the schedule unchanged.

Unlike full neighborhood evaluation, which requires exploring all $\binom{300}{2} = 44{,}850$ combinations at every step, the Simulated Annealing framework samples a single random neighbor per inner iteration. This keeps the computational cost per transition low, relying on the high speed of individual iterations to sample the solution space effectively.

\subsection{Acceptance Criteria and Cooling Schedule}
The core mechanisms regulating exploration in our approach are the cooling profile and the \textit{Metropolis acceptance criterion}. At each step, a candidate neighbor $s'$ is evaluated against the current solution $s$. If the move results in a lower or equal makespan ($\Delta E = f(s') - f(s) \le 0$), the transition is immediately approved, and the algorithm moves to $s'$.

If the move yields a worse makespan ($\Delta E > 0$), it is not automatically discarded. Instead, it is accepted probabilistically based on the following equation:
\begin{equation}
P(\text{accept}) = e^{-\frac{\Delta E}{T}}
\end{equation}

where $\Delta E$ represents the performance degradation ($\Delta C_{max}$) and $T$ is the current temperature. A uniform random float $r \in [0, 1)$ is sampled; if $r < P(\text{accept})$, the worse solution is accepted.

The temperature updates systematically following a geometric cooling schedule:
\begin{equation}
T_{k+1} = \alpha \cdot T_k
\end{equation}

where $\alpha$ is a constant cooling coefficient ($0 < \alpha < 1$). The search terminates when the temperature falls below a specified minimum threshold ($T_{min}$).

