\subsection{Initial Temperature Calibration}
Rather than selecting an arbitrary initial temperature, $T_0$ is calibrated for each problem instance so that the initial acceptance probability of a worsening move is approximately 0.8. This follows the standard methodology for SA parameter setting. The calibration procedure samples 500 random worsening moves from a random initial solution, computes the average worsening delta $\overline{\Delta E}$, and solves for $T_0$:
\begin{equation}
e^{-\overline{\Delta E} / T_0} = 0.8 \quad \Rightarrow \quad T_0 = \frac{-\overline{\Delta E}}{\ln(0.8)}
\end{equation}

This ensures that the algorithm begins with a sufficiently high acceptance probability to explore broadly, regardless of the specific scale of the instance's makespan values. For example, on the \texttt{cscmax\_20\_15\_1} instance, this procedure yields $T_0 \approx 643$.

