\section{Discussion and Conclusion}

\subsection{Summary of Results}
The Simulated Annealing algorithm was tested on 30 Demirkol benchmark instances across two parameter configurations. The improved configuration ($\alpha = 0.97$, $L = 500$) consistently outperformed the baseline ($\alpha = 0.95$, $L = 200$), producing lower makespans with reduced standard deviation across runs. The calibration of the initial temperature $T_0$ to achieve an initial acceptance probability of approximately 0.8 ensured that the algorithm began with sufficient exploration capability for each instance.

Across all 30 instances, performance varied by instance category: the 20-job instances produced the lowest makespans with an average standard deviation of 44.7, the 30-job rcmax instances averaged a standard deviation of 58.1, and the 30-job cscmax instances averaged 74.1. This pattern indicates that the algorithm performs well on smaller and moderately-sized instances but faces increasing difficulty as the problem grows in both size and structural complexity. The cscmax instances proved notably harder than their rcmax counterparts of the same size, suggesting that the processing time distributions in cscmax instances create more challenging bottleneck patterns for the SA search.

The coefficient of variation (CV) across all instances remained below 3.2\%, indicating that the algorithm is robust and produces consistent results across independent runs. The lowest CV values were observed on the 30$\times$20 rcmax instances (e.g., Dmu16 with CV $= 0.68\%$), suggesting that the larger neighborhood in these instances provides more stable search trajectories.

\subsection{Parameter Sensitivity}
The comparison between the baseline and improved configurations demonstrates the sensitivity of SA to the cooling schedule parameters. The slower cooling rate ($\alpha = 0.97$ vs.\ 0.95) and larger Markov chain length ($L = 500$ vs.\ 200) increased the total number of function evaluations from approximately 43,000 to 182,000, providing the algorithm with more opportunities to escape local optima. This resulted in improved solution quality at the cost of increased computation time.

The calibrated $T_0$ values varied across instances (e.g., $T_0 \approx 643$ for the example instance), confirming that the automatic calibration procedure adapts appropriately to the scale of each problem.

