Simulated Annealing achieved the best makespan on 29 out of 30 instances, with the Genetic Algorithm winning on Dmu12. SA also exhibited the lowest standard deviation on the majority of instances, indicating greater robustness across independent runs. In terms of computation time, SA required 9--18 seconds per run compared to 2--9 seconds for TS and 1--2 seconds for GA. However, this difference reflects implementation overhead rather than search effort: all three algorithms performed a comparable number of function evaluations (approximately 180,000--200,000 per run).

The strong performance of SA can be attributed to two factors. First, the automatic calibration of the initial temperature ($T_0$) ensured that the algorithm began with an appropriate level of exploration for each instance. Second, the Metropolis acceptance criterion allowed controlled acceptance of worse solutions throughout the entire search, whereas TS's early stopping rule (100 non-improving iterations) frequently terminated the search before exhausting the computational budget.

To verify that the observed performance differences are statistically significant, a Friedman test was conducted on the Best Objective values across all 30 instances. The test yielded $\chi^2 = 42.87$ with $p < 0.001$, rejecting the null hypothesis of equal performance at $\alpha = 0.05$. Holm post-hoc comparisons confirmed that SA (average rank 1.03) performs significantly better than both TS (average rank 2.37, $p < 0.001$) and GA (average rank 2.60, $p < 0.001$).

\subsection{Limitations}
The proposed SA implementation uses a simple random swap neighborhood, which generates one neighbor per inner iteration. More sophisticated neighborhood operators, such as critical-path-based moves, could significantly improve solution quality. Additionally, the algorithm does not incorporate any problem-specific knowledge such as dispatching rules for initialization, which could provide a better starting point than a random solution.

\subsection{Conclusion}
This study applied Simulated Annealing to the Job Shop Scheduling Problem using 30 Demirkol benchmark instances of varying size and type. The algorithm successfully produced valid schedules for all instances, and achieved a 44.8\% improvement over the initial random solution on the Phase 2 example instance. The parameter sensitivity analysis demonstrated that slower cooling ($\alpha = 0.97$) and longer Markov chains ($L = 500$) meaningfully improve solution quality while maintaining computational times under 18 seconds per run. The automatic calibration of the initial temperature proved effective at adapting the algorithm to different instance scales, with calibrated $T_0$ values ranging from 437 to 946 across the 30 instances.

In the team comparison, SA achieved the best makespan on 29 out of 30 instances, and a Friedman test confirmed that SA (average rank 1.03) is statistically significantly better than both TS (average rank 2.37) and GA (average rank 2.60) at $\alpha = 0.05$ with Holm post-hoc correction. While SA does not match the performance of state-of-the-art JSSP-specific algorithms, it provides a simple, general-purpose approach with very low implementation complexity and consistent behavior, demonstrating that principled parameter calibration can make a basic metaheuristic highly competitive.

